(4, 0, 2, 3, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 1, 0, 'Northern Mendocino County Forest Health Collaborative', null, 2540, 'BLM and Redwood Forest Inc. properties', 2, 2020, null, null, 'This project will treat 1,358 acres on Bureau of Land Management and Redwood Forest Foundation, Inc., properties in Northern Mendocino County. Activies include forest health treatments, shaded fuel break construction, and biomass utilization. Planning includes outreach in Mendocino and Humboldt counties to prepare for critical expansion of fuels reduction work in Phase II. Targeted benefits include enhanced forest health and carbon storage potential, mitigation of wildfire risk, and support for community safety and local employment.'), 
(4, 0, 2, 3, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 1, 0, 'Caspar Gorse Removal', null, 2540, null, 2, 2021, null, null, 'Grant will buy hand tools and pay for local labor to complete hand work to remove gorse and other dangerous fuel loads. This project will also encourage the restoration of sensitive native ecology in collaboration with Jug Handle Non Profit and Fortunate Farm. The majority of work will be completed this fall with subsequent follow up during the next three summers to complete the project.'), 
(4, 0, 2, 3, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 1, 0, 'Mendocino County Fuels Reduction Capacity Building', null, 2540, null, 2, 2021, null, null, 'Purchase of a chipper truck to haul MCFSC-owned chippers and the training of local staff to operate the chipper to support fuels reduction projects across Mendocino County. The project''s goals are to 1) train a new fuels reduction crew to operate vehicles, wood chippers, and other necessary equipment to implement fuels reduction work and 2) decrease long-term costs of fuels reduction activities conducted by the MCFSC by using in-house crews instead of contractors. '), 
(4, 0, 2, 3, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 1, 0, 'Investigating the influence of in-stream large wood and fire on carbon storage in California streams', null, 2540, 'State Forests', 2, 2020, null, null, 'We will address Priority Research Topics 1 and 5 and quantify the amount of in-stream wood and associated stored organic carbon and sediment in three locations. We will assess the potential carbon storage in CA streams, and the effects of past and current fuel reduction management and the impacts of adding wood to streams as a mitigation practice on that potential. We will also determine the effects of wildfire on wood and carbon storage in streams and thus the likely trajectory of in-stream carbon storage under future climate scenarios.'), 
