(4, 0, 2, 3, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 1, 0, 'Ukiah Emergency Fuels Reduction Project', null, 2540, 'Ukiah area - east and west', 3, null, 2019, 2022, 'The Ukiah Fuels Reduction Project consists of 700 acres of vegetation management in critical locations to reduce wildfire intensity and fire rate of spread around the City of Ukiah and surrounding communities. It involves construction of 14 miles of shaded fuel breaks totaling approximately 90 acres on the west and east side of the Ukiah valley adjacent to densely populated housing along the Wildland-Urban-Interface (WUI), approximately 45 miles of fire breaks totaling 160 treated acres on ridgetops in strategic locations, and approximately 450 acres of prescribed burns in brush covered lands to decrease years of accumulated heavy and dead fuels. This project will protect critical Mendocino County resources and community infrastructure from catastrophic wildfire.This emergency project is Phase 1 of a longer-term multi-phase project located within a 26,541acre area surrounding the city of Ukiah.'), 
(4, 0, 2, 3, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 1, 0, 'Usal Redwood Forest', null, 2540, 'Battalion 4: Laytonville/ Leggett/ Percy', 2, 2015, null, null, 'Shaded'), 
(4, 0, 2, 3, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 1, 0, 'Usal Redwood Forest Fuel Reduction & Fire Resiliency Project', null, 2540, 'Usal Redwood Forest', 2, 2020, null, null, 'Our project is the development of a 14 mile shaded fuel break with hazardous fuel reduction along two major trending ridges on Usal Redwood Forest. Emphasis of our project will be to reduce surface fuels, thin from below and raise height and decrease density of the live crown. A combination of mechanical mastication and hand crews will be used. Selected tanoaks removed will be processed into firewood and/or used to create biochar which will be added back into the treatment site soils.'), 
