(4, 0, 2, 3, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, 1, 0, 'Miller Mountain-Little Shasta Valley Hazardous Fuels Reduction and Meadow enhancement', 'Ore-Cal RC&D Council, Tri-State Watershed Improvement Partnership, USFS Goosenest Ranger District (KNF), CALFIRE, California Deer Association, CAL TRANS, CA Department of Fish and Wildlife, US Fish and Wildlife, Shasta Valley RCD, NRCS Yreka Office, Fire Safe Council of Siskiyou County, County of Siskiyou, the community of Little Shasta, private  of timberland and ranching, and the Northern California Resource Center', 2540, null, 2, 2019, null, null, 'Hazardous Fuel Reduction and Wildlife Enhancement, Link to T-WIP document- https://drive.google.com/file/d/1WsZJdFHTRC5F5PSiVzVGmHmwO_E1YxiS/view?usp=sharing , Project Map for Miller Mt. Project combined with meadow restoration area - https://drive.google.com/file/d/1LMZ1aMb1JxmSlPEZ0LSqMEQKyfGR4QDx/view?usp=sharing , 2nd map of Bull Meadows Restoration project, part of Miller Mt. Fuels project - link- https://drive.google.com/file/d/1qDeyoapwc3FGHbbhDQ6qdJai4XzH4YJ9/view?usp=sharing , 
This collaborative and partnership directed strategic planning effort bringing together
Ore-Cal RC&D Council, Tri-State Watershed Improvement Partnership, U.S. Forest
Service, Goosenest Ranger District (Klamath National Forest), BLM, CALFIRE,
California Deer Association, CAL TRANS, CA Department of Fish and Wildlife, US Fish
and Wildlife, Shasta Valley RCD, NRCS Yreka Office, CA School Lands, Fire Safe
Council of Siskiyou County, County of Siskiyou, the community of Little Shasta., private
 of timberland and ranching, and multiple industrial timberland owners,
Siskiyou County Roads Department and Siskiyou County Ag. Department, and the
Northern California Resource Center.
This project is Phase One (300 acres) of an overall proposed project that will eventually
treat approximately 3,000 acres which includes acres along the Forest Boundary, roads,
and defensible space around structures in this high risk WUI area. This initial phase one
of the project will focus on the treatment of 300 acres of forest where Western Juniper
and other native invasives are replacing native grasses and brush which serve as feed
and cover for wildlife with stage three incursion Juniper forests which are less resistant
to wildfire and spread fire rapidly to residences and communities in the vicinity. This
type of project is a high priority of the updated Siskiyou County CWPP.
In the valley floor the project area runs from Sheep Rock next to Hwy A-12 in Shasta
Valley on the south to just north of Table Rock on the north. On the west areas of
planned work include the community of Little Shasta Valley and range to the east to the
edge of Grass Lake. Main population area is a subsection of Little Shasta Valley which
is adjacent to the .City of Montague on the west.
The T-WIP partnership identifies multiple benefits from this work with the main focus
and purpose of the project is to:
• Reduce the threat of catastrophic wildfire to the communities of Little Shasta
Valley and Montague in the wildland urban interface while moving toward a
diverse fire-resilient ecosystem.
• Reduce overstocked, invasive Juniper and brush which are stressed and dying
due to multiple years of drought and return those interface areas to grazing, their
historical vegetative state.
• Enhance early seral foraging and winter range habitat for Mule Deer, Elk,
Antelope, and wild turkeys
• Limit the sediment to streams from historically active sites to improve water
quality.
• Return the forest interface area to native grasses and brush and forbs which
wildlife and cattle can benefit from grazing.
• Measure ground water improvement in wells and stream flows where
opportunities present themselves.
• Find opportunities to reintroduce fire on the landscape where safe and applicable
to return to historic vegetation components. Due to fire exclusion, much of the
juniper is past the effective age to remove with low intensity burns. In the eastside
areas, Western juniper (Juniperus occidentalis) is more easily killed by fires that other conifers
would survive and it invades open sites from rocky refugia during longer fire-free periods.
Siskiyou County CWPP 2019
Project funds will be primarily utilized to perform project preparation, NEPA, layout,
oversight, and acquire crews and equipment to perform fuels reduction and monitoring'), 
